\begin_layout Title
Status consumption and intertemporal substitution
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract

\shape italic
Status consumption is known to be ubiquitous but the role of wealth inequalities
 in status consumption is less understood in the varied contexts of developing
 countries.
 We develop a model for status consumption based on the intertemporal consumer
 choice where status is viewed as part of the consumer's utility.
 The utility function used in the model comprises of both quality in non-durable
 consumption and owned durable goods.
 Using the data on durable goods ownership available in the Tanzanian LSMS
 consumption microdata, we discuss how a segregation of quality may characterise
 status consumption in a developing economy..
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Recent research suggests an ubiquity of status-related consumption and the
 relevance of peer effects in consumer demand 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ChaiKaus2019,KausSA,ZahraIndia,JaikumarConspConIneq,FrieheGermany"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 One expects therefore that regardless of how poor an economy is, the consumers
 would maintain a consumption level relative to their reference group level.
 At an aggregate level, however, a disproportionate demand for items which
 identify the rich consumers (i.e.
 conspicuous consumption) must also depend on the age-composition of the
 consumer population as well as the degree to which the consumers are segregated
 in an economy.
 An insufficient communication amongst the reference groups imposed by region
 or social barriers - could create segregated reference groups and may cause
 the demand for conspicuous goods to be completely absent for some significant
 reference groups.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Similarly, if the poor in an economy are far too many, the poor majority
 may neither observe nor emulate the lifestyles of a rich microscopic minority.
 Such dependence of status consumption on poverty levels has been only partly
 explored by the studies on effects of income inequality on conspicuous
 consumption 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "JaikumarConspConIneq,Duesenberry1949,ChaiKaus2019"
literal "false"

\end_inset


