\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 In the current chapter, we view status consumption as a combination of
 expensive durable goods and high-quality non-durable consumption - comparing
 the two amongst consumers spread across different age-groups and levels
 of urbanisation.
 To endogenise the role of long-term durable goods and personal characteristics
 in status, we use an intertemporal model of consumer choice for status
 consumption.
 The composition of the population and the segregation of quality are viewed
 as life-cycle effects in this intertemporal model.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The view of status as social deference has often been embraced in economics
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "KoutsobinasStatusPoliticalEconomy,corneo_snobbism,ColemanSocialTheory1990"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 - so that it is simply a ranking order in a population of consumers.
 Since the role of status consumption is to influence such a ranking, we
 argue that the status for a consumer with a fixed set of personal characteristi
cs can only be improved either with quality in non-durable consumption or
 with long-term durable goods (including only the durable goods that can
 be part of inter-generational transfers).
 Further, the quality in non-durable consumption may be driven by a certain
 myopia through immediate needs while the consumption of durable goods is
 likely to be driven by the consumer's long-term concerns.
 Thus in an intertemporal model for consumer choice, the representative
 consumer is meant to optimise a utility based on the owned durable goods
 and the quality of non-durable consumption (with a given set of skills
 and characteristics she has acquired over generations).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the conventional demand analysis, the sense of quality is often interpreted
 from an aggregation of items over commodities as separable groups
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "DeatonQualityQuantityVariation,NelsonQualityQuantity,McKelveyQuality2011,McKenzie2005,GibsonKimQualityBog2019,DongShonkwierCappsQualityQuantity"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 As the theoretical requirements for such an aggregation require a detailed
 set of market prices of goods within every commodity
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "DeatonQualityQuantityVariation,NelsonQualityQuantity"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, the view of status consumption as high-quality consumption is often hampered
 with a lack of information on brand/type variety in the typical consumption
 survey.
 To circumvent this issue, the studies on conspicuous consumption often
 focus on a particular instance of status consumption - comprising of (visible)
 goods that are meant to be futile for the general needs of the consumer.
 The futility of status goods ensures the separability of demand for visible
 goods.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We argue that the futility assumption cannot be made in severely unequal
 societies where wealth differences may be far too wide to be narrowed with
 visible (or high quality) non-durable consumption.
 In other words, since status consumption comprises both of quality across
 commodities and ownership of durable goods in our model, the contribution
 of durable goods to the ranking order might dominate any changes with visible
 (high quality) non-durable consumption.
 Evaluating this framework in the particular case of Tanzania, we discuss
 how quality in non-durable consumption is segregated by personal characteristic
s (e.g.
 education) and availability of certain durable goods.
 The consideration of wealth - which we proxy with durable goods in the
 data - provide us the means to identify status consumption in a developing
 economy and allows us to measure its significance in an economy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\bar under
our goal is to extend this model to other countries - without running into
 the issues of visibility surveys - and avoiding being limited to visible
 consumption.
 The eventual goal is to have a framework to test whether status consumption
 is significant in an economy - and more importantly, how would it vary
 between the developed and developing economies.
\end_layout

