 Since most of empirical data is gathered at household levels, the larger
 households having more needs would require the consumption data to be scaled
 by the number of members.
 One must standardise the basic needs of a household to establish such a
 reference level.
 Second is the local social reference levels for status consumption.
 If the choice consumer faces is to either save for future or spend on status
 goods, she is likely to be concerned with the rich consumption in her immediate
 social surroundings rather than a distant (possibly richer) consumer.
\end_layout

