 Assuming the needs of the family (indicated by the number of family members)
 haven't changed, the consumption would either shift to saving for a better
 car or improve quality in some other category (better jewelry, better schooling
 for kids etc.) in response to price changes or a equivalent changes in income.
 The sensitivity of consumption with respect to price thus comprises of
 sensitivity with respect to basic needs 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\partial c_{t}}{\partial\Psi_{t}}$
\end_inset

as well as a sensitivity with respect to quality for each commodity 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\partial c_{t}}{\partial\nu_{t}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 The assumed structure of 
\begin_inset Formula $\upsilon(\Psi,\nu,A)$
\end_inset

 implies that a consumer could achieve the same utility - inclusive of status
 - as that of a consumer with a higher education or higher durable goods
 ownership (higher 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

) by raising her excess non-durable consumption (or quality).
 This would accommodate the likely clusters of 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

 associated with a characteristics 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 (e.g education, housing, identity, region or barriers owing to segregation,
 trade barriers etc.).
 In other words, a peer effects approach is readily incorporated in the
 model (see Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Peer-Effects-Simplification"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 for details ).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is worth emphasising that status is not considered a need using this
 approach.
 Instead, it is inherent in the consumer's demand for quality and the level
 of durable goods ownership she achieves while her basic needs are independent
 of her wealth.
 The aggregate sense of status through consumption is derived by both expensive
 durable goods and quality (across all commodities) - driven by wealth and
 income of the consumer (rather than high-class or low-class needs of the
 consumer).
 As an example, the difference between the status of a rich and that of
 a poor family in our model is not through disparate educational needs of
 the rich and poor children but instead through a more general need for
 the family combined with a demand for quality for education (with a higher
 price for higher quality).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The consideration of a consumer's wealth - which separate the rich and non-rich
 consumers - is assumed to be encompassed by the accumulated durable (
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

) and long-term characteristics 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 (education, occupation or social identity) in the model.
 The ownership of durable goods is modeled with an asset account - whose
 value is reflected in the total cost of durable goods.
 The use of such an asset account implies that no distinction is made between
 the accumulation of cash reserved to purchase durable goods and the actual
 purchase of durable goods.
 Thus if a consumer sets her eyes on durable goods 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 (that have prices 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{A}<\Pi_{B}$
\end_inset

) and the value of her cash account at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{t}=\Pi_{A}$
\end_inset

, then the model does not distinguish between the case when she buys the
 durable goods 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 (price 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{A}$
\end_inset

) and the case when she forgoes the purchase of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 to save for the future purchase of 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 ( since 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{B}>\Pi_{A}$
\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another way to view the asset account is to consider that all long-term
 durable goods in the economy are managed by a large firm (owing its success
 to preferences being the same for everybody) that provides furniture, housing
 and all amenities at a flat upfront cost.
 Every durable goods  and service - offered as a life-long subscription
 - can be purchased by giving an amount to this company.
 We also assume that at the of the lifetime of a consumer, her personal
 wealth would either be consumed or would be passed on to her progeny so
 that the asset account at the end of the lifetime becomes starting wealth
 of some other household(s) in the economy.
 Consequently, while all individuals in the population are assumed to be
 the same as our representative consumer in terms of the preferences for
 needs over quality, they do differ in the the starting amount of their
 asset accounts as well as the trends of their salaries.
 The quality habits of quality (
\shape italic
excess
\shape default
) depend on these long-term characteristics.
 If a consumer has a starting income 
\begin_inset Formula $i_{0}$
\end_inset

 and her salary after 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 years of working is 
\begin_inset Formula $i_{\tau}$
\end_inset

 then at a given time 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

, she could have purchased some long-term durable-goods from a portion of
 her income - deciding that she does not want more durable goods for the
 rest of her life.
 Alternatively, she could have experienced a change in the life-circumstances
 (needing a bigger or a more expensive house) thus needing more durable
 goods urgently.
 The consumption in the period 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 would therefore depend on the needs 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi_{\tau}$
\end_inset

, asset account value 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\tau}$
\end_inset

 and the consumption of quality 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{\tau}$
\end_inset

 in the period 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

.
 Due to the minimal presence of credit facilities in the developing countries,
 we assume a negligible credit in the market.
 This in turn implies that the consumer can only save to buy more of the
 only durable goods available in the market.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To separate the measures of wealth from the long-term characteristics that
 drive the household income, we use an income process that is estimated
 exogenously.
 Unlike in PIH, the accumulation of long-term durable goods have an influence
 on the substitution between savings and quality in the intertemporal setting
 we have chosen.
 What this means empirically is that while the exogenous income process
 may depend on education or occupation levels, the effect that long-term
 characteristics have on consumption are not necessarily through income
 but through the constraints associated with levels of durable goods ownership.
 As the effects of on consumption are modeled explicitly, it would suffice
 if the income process models only the monetary growth i.e.
 a reflection of the steady growth in the economy on the consumer's budget
 (in analysis of the Tanzanian data in the current chapter, an income process
 dependent on long-term characteristics such as education and occupation
 is assumed).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:nonstochproblem"

\end_inset

Dynamic Optimisation Problem
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By definition of the needs, a consumer is meant to select a quality control
 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{t}$
\end_inset

 only after her basic needs and those imposed by the owned durable goods
 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{t}$
\end_inset

 are fulfilled.
 As stated earlier, the control for quality (
\shape italic
excess
\shape default
) 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{t}$
\end_inset

 (in period 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

) is simply the distance in terms of money from the cost of needs 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi_{t}$
\end_inset

 for the household.
 The higher its value, higher would be the distance from needs consumption
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi_{t}$
\end_inset

 (and lower would be the future growth of 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{t}$
\end_inset

).
 Other than the control 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{t}$
\end_inset

, the consumption depends both on needs and the long-term choices of the
 consumer (which are encapsulated by 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{t}$
\end_inset

 the consumer has accumulated in the past and the the personal characteristics
 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 she possesses).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The non-durable costs imposed by the durable goods one possesses (e.g.
 fuel for cars, electricity for heating equipment, rent/maintenance-fees
 for housing etc.) imply either that avoiding the respective expenses is
 not an option for the consumer owning some durable goods or that some certain
 long-term choices or characteristics (e.g.
 not having a house or living in a region that doesn't have electricity
 available) would limit the choice to avail quality through non-durable
 consumption.
 As discussed in the Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:MeasuringNQA"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, the extended necessities of the consumer as she acquires durable goods
 are considered the part of needs cost 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi_{t}$
\end_inset

.
 The effect of any supply-related asymmetries in the data e.g.
 lack of availability of certain goods in a certain region etc.
 are all accommodated in the costs 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi_{t}$
\end_inset

 as well.
 Given a utility function over quality 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 a consumer is set to optimise the combined utility over the period of her
 life-time by choosing 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{t}$
\end_inset

 in every period as her income 
\begin_inset Formula $i_{t}$
\end_inset

 changes and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi_{t}$
\end_inset

 change.
 The intertemporal substitution between durable goods 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{t}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{t}$
\end_inset

 imply that a consumer may want to save for durable goods 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{t}$
\end_inset

 or consumer more on short-term quality 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{t}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The simplest instance of intertemporal substitution is a two period model
 where durable goods are meant to be liquidated at the end of the second
 period.
 We choose this model as 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{gather}
u_{1}=a_{1}log(\Psi_{1})+blog(A_{0})+(1-a_{1}-b)log(\nu_{1})\label{eq:twoperiodoptim}\\
u_{2}=a_{2}log(\Psi_{2})+blog(A_{1})+(1-a_{2}-b)log(\nu_{2})\nonumber 
\end{gather}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here, 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{1},\nu_{2}$
\end_inset

 are consumption on quality in periods 1 and 2 respectively while 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{0},A_{1}$
\end_inset

 are value of durable goods at start of the periods.
 Notice that the utility of long-term durable goods is not supposed to change
 for the consumer over her life-time.
 In a typical solution of the intertemporal problem, the wealth constraint
 for the optimisation of 
\begin_inset Formula $U=u_{0}+u_{1}$
\end_inset

 would consider the final 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{2}$
\end_inset

 (i.e.
 all of the consumer's durable goods being liquidated and consumed in the
 last period) and the discounting rate based on 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

.
 However, since we observe the change in asset account at every period in
 our model, we take a slightly different approach with a dynamic optimisation
 formulation and write the growth of durable goods as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{gather*}
A_{1}=A_{0}(1+r)+i_{1}-\nu_{1}-\Psi_{1}\\
A_{2}=A_{1}(1+r)+i_{2}-\nu_{2}-\Psi_{2}
\end{gather*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Above signifies that the consumer may consume quality 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{2}$
\end_inset

 ( 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{3...}$
\end_inset

 being undefined) in the periods 1 and 2 while she bears the cost of the
 needs 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi_{1},\Psi_{2}$
\end_inset

 (in periods 1 and 2 respectively).
 The intertemporal substitution implies that she may save for growth to
 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{2}$
\end_inset

 instead of consuming all her income 
\begin_inset Formula $i_{t}$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{t}=\nu_{t}+\Psi_{t}$
\end_inset

 i.e.
 she can spend all her income 
\begin_inset Formula $i_{1},i_{2}$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{1},c_{2}$
\end_inset

 (respectively) or save some of it towards 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{1},A_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 If we observe the states of the wealth - 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{0},A_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{2}$
\end_inset

, consumption 
\begin_inset Formula $\{c_{1},c_{2}\},$
\end_inset

 cost of necessities 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\Psi_{1},\Psi_{2}\}$
\end_inset

, the rate of growth of money (interest rate) 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 and an exogenous income process 
\begin_inset Formula $i_{t}$
\end_inset

, then we can solve for the parameters that govern the utility function
 additive over time i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $u=u_{1}+u_{2}$
\end_inset

 .
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To motivate a more general dynamic optimisation approach, consider first
 what consumer's choices would be in a one-period consumption.
 Here, she could either spend all income 
\begin_inset Formula $i_{1}$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{_{1}}=\nu_{1}+\Psi_{1}$
\end_inset

 or keep the minimum consumption (
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{1}=0,c_{1}=\Psi_{1}$
\end_inset

) in the period and end up with 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{1}>A_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 If we can set 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{0}=0$
\end_inset

, then the first-order conditions would provide us the optimal condition
 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 Let this utility be 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{1}^{*}$
\end_inset

 due to 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{1}^{*},A_{1}^{*}$
\end_inset

.
 To extend this to two periods with dynamic optimisation one can exploit
 the fact that a consumer independently optimising 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{1}+u_{2}$
\end_inset

 would always obtain 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{1}^{*}+u_{2}^{*}$
\end_inset

.
 This is because if 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{2}$
\end_inset

 are unbounded functions 
\begin_inset Formula $max(u_{1}+u_{2})\le max(u_{1})+max(u_{2})=u_{1}^{*}+u_{2}^{*}$
\end_inset

.
 Setting 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{0}=0$
\end_inset

 is only a tool to formulate the dynamic optimisation approach - using which
 the expected value of utility is to be optimised over her life period in
 a 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

-period model (
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 being the age of the consumer).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The changes in expected utility per period are what drive her behaviour
 at every period 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 and her choice is set to vary according to her age 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 (assuming that all consumers have similar expectations for the trajectory
 of their needs).
 A steady state would thus be achieved with ages 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 .
 The conditions of stability of the steady state imply that while consumers
 maintain different 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{t}$
\end_inset

, they are a function of characteristics 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 and age 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here, the notion that a consumer may change her behaviour away from the
 current plan in the future is fallacious since a consumer observed at different
 ages is equivalent to consumers of varied ages at any point in time (see
 Deaton's clarification of the so-called dynamic inconsistency problem
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "DeatonUnderstandingConsumption"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 In other words, the behaviour of an older consumer is the same as the future
 behaviour of a younger consumer.
 So the optimal solution for the total sum 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i=1}^{T-t}u_{i}$
\end_inset

 would apply both to the individuals of all ages as well as an individual
 observed over a number of years.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Peer-Effects-Simplification"

\end_inset

Peer Effects
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the model specified in Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:twoperiodoptim"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, it is not possible for the consumer to compensate for 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{t}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{t}$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed the more educated people or those in better occupations (or those
 with higher perceived class) might need less durable goods and less quality
 to indicate status.
 We therefore include 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 (which is static for the consumer) as part of the consumer utility by letting
 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 depend on 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Due to the high upfront cost attached to owning long-term durable goods,
 there may be a certain levelling effect to the extent to which durable
 goods may be used to compensate for not having the most favourable 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

.
 Thus the effect of 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 may dominate the choice for non-durable consumption.
 In other words, ownership of 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{t}$
\end_inset

 is quite likely to be segregated amongst those with different 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

.
 An influential or a high-status 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 has two competing roles for the consumer utility - first, it allows the
 consumer to not require as many durable goods as those in a lower 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

.
 Second, it requires the consumer to maintain a certain level that is required
 of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 she possesses.
 This interplay of 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{t}$
\end_inset

 is allows us to model the role of peer effects - i.e.
 that claim that the consumers consider quality relative to her reference
 group rather than an absolute level.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If peer effects were to be modeled explicitly, let's say through a distance
 from average 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

 calculated over 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 (or over an ordinal class
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ChaiKaus2019"
literal "false"

\end_inset

), then as long as the higher status rank (part of 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

) are also wealthy, the consumer with a high status rank due to 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 would also need to keep up the quality consumption to her wealthier reference
 level.
 Therefore, those in the higher rank (e.g.
 higher status occupations etc.) would benefit both from being in a higher
 status group (
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

) and from the higher durable goods possession that entails being in the
 high status group (
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

).
 To avoid double-counting for the effect that 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 has on the utility, we choose only the characteristics 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 that form the reference group over which the distance from average consumption
 is considered relevant for peer effects.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Some recent literature has found an ordinal treatment of status more suitable
 for modeling status-related consumption.
 We believe that the properties of the average over the particular personal
 characteristics 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 allows us to consider an ordinal treatment without losing the tractability
 of averages in estimation.
 If we are sure to consider only the 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 that can serve as a reference group for consumption, then the presence
 of peer effects only means that the consumer does not worry about having
 less 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

 than the average of a community (
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 ) which she does not consider herself a member of.
 Instead, the utility derived by being ahead of the local average (of quality
 or durable goods) i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 is more significant to her.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To consider what this simplification offers to the econometric methods to
 follow, consider a market of just quality (and no durable goods) as an
 illustration.
 Here, a model for utility through 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

 can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula $S=a\nu+b\int_{\rho}f_{\nu}d\nu$
\end_inset

 which is similar to the Ireland's signaling model
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ireland_signals"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 - in the sense that the utility is a combination of private and public
 sub-utilities.
 The model for 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 can be decomposed as 
\begin_inset Formula $S=a\nu+b\int_{\rho}f_{\nu}d\nu$
\end_inset

 or
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{alignat}{1}
S & =a(\nu-\int_{\rho}f_{\nu}d\nu)+(a+b)\int_{\rho}f_{\nu}d\nu)\label{eq:peer_effects_decomposition}
\end{alignat}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Above can be interpreted as how the total utility can be seen as a combination
 of the sub-utility from the distance in quality from the local average
 and that from the overall effect of 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

.
 This interpretation permits us to approximate the first term with a function
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

 and the second term with a function solely of 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

.
 The consumer thus maintains both a relative advantage and the collective
 absolute advantage from quality - without issues of double-accounting.
 The approach would not change if difference in durable goods were introduced
 in the model.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is worth emphasising that the measurement of distance from needs which
 we track with 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

 is not a measure of peer effects in itself.
 The distance from needs 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

 in fact only encompasses the higher price of the items or their consumed
 quantity.
 As 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

 reflects spatial variation in prices, the controls for spatial variation
 must be included in the 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 over which peer effects are considered (second term in the equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:peer_effects_decomposition"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 More generally, the characteristics 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 that may serve as an appropriate cluster over which 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{\rho}f_{\nu}d\nu$
\end_inset

 is evaluated are driven by the particular dataset at hand.
 Out of the characteristics like region, occupation or education, one may
 be more important than others in a particular context.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The intertemporal substitution
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With the introduction of 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{\rho}$
\end_inset

 and the peer effects simplification discussed in the Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Peer-Effects-Simplification"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, the utility function can be written as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{alignat}{1}
u_{\tau}(\tau,\rho) & =a_{\tau}log(\Psi_{\tau})+b_{\rho}log(A_{\tau})+(1-a_{\tau}-b_{\rho})log(\nu_{\tau})\label{eq:mainequation}
\end{alignat}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 is the age of the household (i.e.
 that of the household head).
 The model relies on the assumption that the utility factor for quality
 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{\tau}$
\end_inset

 (i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $1-a_{\tau}-b_{\rho}$
\end_inset

) changes both with age 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

, the utility factor for needs 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi_{t}$
\end_inset

 (i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{\tau}$
\end_inset

) changes with only 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 (not with 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

) and the factor for durable goods 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\tau}$
\end_inset

 (i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{\rho}$
\end_inset

) changes only with characteristics 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Ideally, we should use a measure of needs rather the cost of needs.
 We use 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi_{t}$
\end_inset

 not only because it is observed directly (rather than the quantities which
 are not observed) but also because it encapsulates the regional variation
 in prices.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 The last assumption rests upon the definition of long-term durable goods
 being intergenerational (and thus long-term enough for their utility to
 not change over time).
 The subscript 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{\tau}$
\end_inset

 is used to signify that 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{\tau}$
\end_inset

 does not change with personal characteristics the way 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{\rho}$
\end_inset

 does not change with age 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

.
 The utility that the consumer gets from from the same level of quality
 and long-term durable would - on the other hand - vary with both personal
 characteristics (reference group) 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 and age 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

.
 Due to the very definition of needs, preference of the total cost of needs
 does not vary with 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Notice that since 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 signifies the term 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{\rho}\nu d\nu$
\end_inset

 it also encompasses the peer effects arising out of the reference group
 identity.
